<subSubSection id="C306BDAFFF90AC0AE8A5EEC4FE03E439" pageId="6" pageNumber="141" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BA3EE24FF90AC0AE8A5EEC4FE03E439" blockId="6.[159,670,196,719]" pageId="6" pageNumber="141">Etymology.—Name is based on the partly orange abdomen.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C306BDAFFF90AC0AE8A5ED1AFD42E4FE" pageId="6" pageNumber="141" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BA3EE24FF90AC0AE8A5ED1AFD42E4FE" blockId="6.[159,670,196,719]" pageId="6" pageNumber="141">Remarks.—The yellow orbits, upper and lower margins of the pronotum, axillae, metanotum, and fifth, sixth, and apical segments of the abdomen will distinguish this species. The diverging eyes below and short sheath are also helpful.</paragraph>
